functions.label: getESQLAdHocDataview
description:
Creates an ad-hoc DataView for ES|QL queries.

Some applications need to have a DataView to work properly with ES|QL queries.
This helper creates an ad-hoc DataView with an ID constructed from the index pattern.
Since there are no runtime fields, field formatters, or default time fields,
the same ad-hoc DataView can be constructed/reused, which solves caching issues
described in https://github.com/elastic/kibana/issues/168131.

The function automatically detects the time field by making an HTTP request to determine
if '@timestamp' exists across all indices in the query. If all indices contain the field,
it sets '@timestamp' as the time field; otherwise, no time field is set.
signature: ; query: string; options?: { allowNoIndex?: boolean | undefined; createNewInstanceEvenIfCachedOneAvailable?: boolean | undefined; skipFetchFields?: boolean | undefined; } | undefined; http?:

children.label: options
signature: { allowNoIndex?: boolean | undefined; createNewInstanceEvenIfCachedOneAvailable?: boolean | undefined; skipFetchFields?: boolean | undefined; } | undefined

returnComment: Promise that resolves to the created DataView with the detected time field (if any)

functions.label: getInitialESQLQuery
description:
Builds an ES|QL query for the provided dataView
If there is @timestamp field in the index, we don't add the WHERE clause
If there is no @timestamp and there is a dataView timeFieldName, we add the WHERE clause with the timeFieldName
If the index pattern contains TSDB fields, we add the TS command, otherwise we add the FROM command

- `fork` commands where ALL branches contain only transformational commands
